      answer: "A threat model answers four questions before you touch a single line of security code:\n\n- **What are we protecting?** (tokens, PII, payment data, health records)\n- **Who might attack it?** (curious user, ex-employee, nation-state, automated script)\n- **How could they reach it?** (network, physical device, reverse-engineering the bundle)\n- **What is the acceptable risk?** (losing a session token vs. losing a social-security number are different severities)\n\nWithout a threat model you end up either **over-engineering** (pinning certificates for a todo app) or **under-protecting** (storing a credit card number in AsyncStorage because it's easy).\n\nFor most React Native apps the top three real threats are:\n\n1. Sensitive data left on disk in plaintext (logs, AsyncStorage, SQLite).\n2. Network traffic readable on a coffee-shop Wi-Fi (no HTTPS enforcement, no pinning).\n3. Hardcoded secrets extracted from the JS bundle by a moderately curious attacker.\n\nStart there. Add more threat categories only after you have covered those basics.",
