      answer: "`AsyncStorage` stores data as plain files on disk — on Android under `/data/data/<package>/files/` and on iOS under the app's `Documents/` directory. Neither location is protected by the OS keychain or hardware-backed encryption.\n\nThe two main problems:\n\n- **Root / jailbreak access.** On a rooted Android or jailbroken iOS device any app (or attacker) can read every file in your app's storage directory without any privilege escalation. Encrypting the value yourself just shifts the question: where is the key? If the key is also in AsyncStorage you have solved nothing.\n- **iTunes / ADB backups.** An attacker with physical access to a laptop that backed up the phone can extract the entire AsyncStorage folder with a single command — no root required.\n\n**The rule:** AsyncStorage is for UI preferences, cached responses, non-sensitive state. Tokens, passwords, private keys, and PII belong in `expo-secure-store` (iOS Keychain / Android Keystore) — hardware-backed, excluded from backups by default, and never accessible to other apps.",
