      answer: "HTTPS encrypts the transport layer (TLS) so that traffic between the app and server cannot be read in transit by a third party on the same network. Enforcing HTTPS is the **floor**, not the ceiling.\n\nWhy it is not enough alone:\n\n- **MITM via a trusted proxy certificate.** Any attacker who installs a custom root CA on the device (easy on Android, possible on jailbroken iOS) can intercept HTTPS traffic transparently. Charles Proxy and mitmproxy do exactly this — it's how developers debug network traffic, and it's how attackers inspect yours.\n- **Certificate validation bugs.** Libraries can be misconfigured to accept expired or self-signed certs (`rejectUnauthorized: false` is a common shortcut that forgets to be reverted).\n- **App Transport Security (ATS) bypass.** On iOS you can add `NSAllowsArbitraryLoads: true` to `Info.plist` to silence ATS warnings during dev, then accidentally ship it.\n\n**Layered approach:**\n1. HTTPS everywhere (no plaintext fallback).\n2. ATS enabled (iOS) / cleartext disabled (Android).\n3. Certificate pinning for your own API endpoints.\n4. Request signing so stolen tokens can't be replayed.",
