      answer: "Certificate pinning tells the app to **only trust a specific certificate or public key** for a given hostname — not just any certificate signed by a trusted CA. Even if an attacker installs a custom root CA on the device and intercepts the TLS handshake, the app sees that the certificate does not match its pinned value and refuses the connection.\n\n**Three pinning strategies (increasing resilience):**\n\n- **Leaf certificate pin** — pin the exact cert. Simple to implement, breaks every time the cert rotates (typically every 1–2 years).\n- **Intermediate CA pin** — pin your CA's intermediate certificate. Survives leaf rotation, but requires you control your CA.\n- **Public key pin (SPKI)** — pin the Subject Public Key Info hash. The cert can rotate (expire, re-issue) as long as the keypair stays the same. Most resilient.\n\n**The operational risk:** if you lose the pinned keypair or forget to ship an app update before the pinned cert expires, every user on the current version loses connectivity — a self-inflicted outage. Mitigations:\n\n- Always pin **two keys**: the current + a backup (kept offline).\n- Ship the update with the new pin before the old cert expires.\n- Provide a **fallback endpoint** (without pinning) that returns a human-readable error so users know to update.\n\nFor Expo apps: use a Turbo Native Module wrapping `TrustKit` (iOS) or `OkHttp CertificatePinner` (Android) — the JS layer cannot intercept the TLS handshake itself.",
